{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves the meaning of the source text, not just a word-for-word substitution.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP applies directly: this behavior is about translation quality/meaning preservation, which depends on real model judgment and can vary across runs. A stubbed translator would hide real failures in fluency/semantic adequacy. I considered Workflow and rejected it because the behavior text describes a single model output quality check, not multiple agentic steps in sequence.","test_description":"Run evaluation prompts through the real NMT API on a fixed bilingual benchmark set; score semantic adequacy and grammaticality (human rubric or model-assisted rubric with spot checks) and fail if thresholds/regressions are exceeded versus baseline.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.86,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the translation API returns a 503 error, the service transparently falls back to the dictionary-based translator without returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS indicates a module handoff failure boundary: API client error -> service fallback -> response shaping. This needs multiple local modules wired together, but not real network/OS behavior. I considered System and rejected it because the behavior text is specifically about handling a 503 condition and transparent fallback, not transport-layer/network phenomena.","test_description":"Wire service + API client interface + SQLite-backed fallback in-process. Make the API client return a 503-equivalent error object/exception, assert HTTP success to caller with dictionary translation body, and assert no propagated upstream error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The dictionary-based fallback returns the correct pre-stored translation for phrases that exist in the SQLite database.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is repository/query + SQLite persistence mapping, not pure function logic. Using a real local SQLite DB is needed to catch schema/query/collation mistakes; this is still Integration (local DB/filesystem), not System. I considered Unit and rejected it because the behavior explicitly requires correctness of retrieval from SQLite.","test_description":"Create a temporary SQLite DB with known phrase rows, run fallback translator against existing phrases, and assert exact stored translations are returned (including case/diacritics rules expected by schema).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The quality tracking comparison correctly computes edit distance between primary and fallback outputs and stores the metric.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior spans algorithm + persistence handoff (compute metric then store). Unit tests can validate edit-distance math, but real failure can occur at module wiring/storage boundary (wrong field, missing write, transaction issue). I considered Agentic and rejected it because correctness here is deterministic string-distance computation/storage, not model-output quality.","test_description":"Use deterministic primary/fallback strings with known edit distance, execute quality-tracking path end-to-end with local DB, then assert stored metric value and associated translation record IDs/timestamps are correct.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When both translators are available, the service returns the primary translation and logs the quality comparison in the background.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration across components plus async side-effect verification: primary result selection + background quality logging. In-process integration with controlled stubs and local storage is sufficient to expose real ordering/handoff bugs. I considered Agentic and rejected it because behavior checks routing/precedence/background logging, not whether model content is semantically good.","test_description":"Run service with both translators returning deterministic outputs; assert immediate response equals primary output, then wait/poll for background task completion and verify quality metric log row was persisted without blocking request latency path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
